  "final_answer": "## Assessment: AI Segment Most Likely to Experience Future Depreciation Expansion\n\n### Conclusion\n\nThe **AI segment** is, by a wide margin, the segment most likely to experience material future depreciation expansion. This conclusion is supported by the interplay of capex intensity, absolute capex scale, the surging construction-in-progress balance, and the short useful lives of the segment's dominant asset class.\n\n---\n\n### I. FY2025 Capex Intensity Analysis\n\nCapex intensity is measured as capital expenditures as a percentage of segment revenue:\n\n| Segment | FY2025 Capex | FY2025 Revenue | Capex Intensity |\n|---------|-------------|----------------|-----------------|\n| **AI** | $12,727M | $3,201M | **397.6%** |\n| Space | $3,832M | $4,086M | 93.8% |\n| Connectivity | $4,178M | $11,387M | 36.7% |\n| **Total** | $20,737M | $18,674M | 111.0% |\n\nAI's capex intensity of 397.6% is an extreme outlier—capex runs at nearly four times segment revenue. This means AI is building an asset base vastly disproportionate to its current revenue scale. Every dollar of capex eventually flows through the income statement as depreciation, creating an enormous embedded future depreciation burden.\n\n---\n\n### II. Depreciation Trajectory by Segment (FY2023–FY2025)\n\n| Segment | FY2023 D&A | FY2024 D&A | FY2025 D&A | 2-Year CAGR | FY2025 D&A as % of Segment Revenue |\n|---------|------------|------------|------------|-------------|-------------------------------------|\n| **AI** | $1,180M | $1,679M | **$3,568M** | **73.9%** | **111.5%** |\n| Connectivity | $884M | $1,508M | $2,376M | 63.9% | 20.9% |\n| Space | $571M | $637M | $757M | 15.1% | 18.5% |\n\nAI depreciation and amortization already:\n- Represents **53.2%** of total company D&A ($3,568M / $6,701M)\n- **Exceeds AI segment revenue** (111.5% of revenue)\n- Is growing at the fastest CAGR (73.9%)\n\nThe trend is already steeply upward, and the forward pipeline is far larger.\n\n---\n\n### III. The Construction-in-Progress Time Bomb\n\nThe most critical forward-looking indicator is the construction-in-progress (CIP) balance:\n\n| Date | CIP Balance |\n|------|-------------|\n| December 31, 2025 | $4,604M |\n| March 31, 2026 | **$14,045M** |\n| **Single-quarter increase** | **$9,441M** |\n\nNote 5 explicitly states: *\"Construction in progress is primarily comprised of ongoing construction and expansion of the facilities and equipment as well as AI infrastructure that has not yet been placed in service.\"*\n\nThe MD&A attributes AI capex growth to *\"investments in the rapid expansion of our terrestrial data centers, including the development, construction, and equipping of new facilities and supporting infrastructure.\"*\n\nThe Q1 2026 AI capex alone was $7,723M—annualizing to approximately **$30.9B**. The vast majority of the $14.0B CIP balance is AI-related. When these assets are placed in service, depreciation will experience a step-function increase.\n\n---\n\n### IV. Asset Composition and Useful Lives\n\nAI's primary PP&E categories and their disclosed useful lives:\n\n| Asset Category | Gross Balance (Dec 31, 2025) | Useful Life | Depreciation Profile |\n|----------------|------------------------------|-------------|---------------------|\n| Servers and networking equipment | $22,694M | **5–6 years** | Rapid, front-loaded recognition |\n| Data center infrastructure | $2,960M | 20–25 years | Slow, long-duration recognition |\n| CIP (predominantly AI) | $4,604M (→ $14,045M at Q1 2026) | Not yet depreciating | Future step-change upon placement in service |\n\nThe servers-and-networking category—AI's dominant asset—carries the **shortest useful life** (5–6 years) among all major PP&E categories (satellites: 3–5 years; launch sites: 7–20 years; data center infrastructure: 20–25 years). This means each dollar of AI server capex converts to annual depreciation at roughly 17–20% of the gross asset value, a far faster rate than data center infrastructure (4–5%) or launch sites.\n\nBy contrast:\n- **Connectivity's** satellites (3–5 years) also depreciate rapidly, but capex intensity (36.7%) is far lower and revenue is large enough ($11.4B) to absorb depreciation growth.\n- **Space's** launch sites (7–20 years) and flight vehicle hardware (depreciated per-flight over 5–25 flights) generate far slower depreciation relative to asset base.\n\n---\n\n### V. Key Assumptions Required to Support This Conclusion\n\n1. **CIP will be placed into service.** The $14.0B CIP balance—predominantly AI data center infrastructure—must be substantially completed and transferred to depreciable PP&E. If projects are delayed or cancelled, the depreciation step-up would not materialize as projected.\n\n2. **AI capex pace continues or moderates only gradually.** The Q1 2026 annualized run-rate of ~$30.9B suggests acceleration, not deceleration. If capex falls sharply, the depreciation pipeline would be smaller—but the existing CIP alone guarantees substantial expansion.\n\n3. **Asset mix within AI capex skews toward shorter-lived assets.** The analysis assumes a meaningful portion of AI capex goes to servers and networking equipment (5–6 year life) rather than exclusively to data center shell infrastructure (20–25 year life). The MD&A references \"development, construction, and equipping\" of data centers, and the $22.7B servers balance confirms significant server investment. If future AI capex shifts heavily toward long-lived data center shells, depreciation expansion would be more gradual.\n\n4. **No material change in estimated useful lives.** If management extends server useful lives (e.g., from 5–6 to 7–8 years), annual depreciation would be lower than projected under current assumptions.\n\n5. **No material impairment of AI assets.** A large impairment charge (as occurred in FY2023 with a $3,775M AI impairment) would reduce the gross asset base and thus future depreciation. The filing does not forecast impairments.\n\n6. **AI revenue growth trajectory.** Whether depreciation expansion creates an earnings problem depends on revenue growth. If AI revenue scales rapidly, depreciation as a percentage of revenue may decline even as absolute depreciation rises (as seen in Connectivity, where the MD&A notes costs will \"increase in absolute dollars\" but \"decrease as a percentage of revenue\"). The filing does not provide sufficient information to conclude whether AI revenue will outgrow its depreciation burden.\n\n---\n\n### VI. Distinction from Disclosure vs. Inference\n\n- **Explicitly disclosed**: Segment capex, segment D&A, CIP balance and its AI-heavy composition, useful lives, and historical trends are all directly reported in the S-1.\n- **Reasonable inference**: The mapping of CIP to AI, the projection that CIP conversion will drive depreciation expansion, and the asset-mix assumption are inferences grounded in disclosed magnitudes and management commentary.\n- **Not disclosed**: Forward-looking depreciation guidance, segment-level PP&E balances, quantitative CIP split by segment, and future capex plans are not provided.",
